    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:06dc07d4-0839-45b0-9e40-069b307c06ed",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 63-year-old retired schoolteacher who lives alone in a quiet suburban neighborhood following her divorce twelve years ago. She is a warm, meticulous woman who fills her days gardening, attending a weekly watercolor painting class, and volunteering at her local library. She has two adult daughters with whom she maintains a close and loving relationship, and a tight-knit circle of friends from her years in education. Standing 5'4\" and weighing 72 kg, she has a medium build and carries herself with a composed dignity that belies the anxiety she has felt since her diagnosis. Her hair, which began thinning modestly after chemotherapy, is now covered by colorful headscarves she has embraced with characteristic grace.\n\n{patientName} first noticed a firm, painless lump in her right breast approximately eight months ago during her monthly self-examination routine — a habit she had maintained since her mother's breast cancer diagnosis decades earlier. She initially dismissed it as a benign cyst, but growing concern prompted her to seek medical attention after three weeks. She reports no nipple discharge or skin changes at presentation, though mild skin dimpling was subsequently identified on ultrasound-guided examination. She denies any systemic complaints such as bone pain, shortness of breath, or unintentional weight loss at this time.\n\nOn review of systems, {patientName} does report moderate fatigue, which she attributes partly to her chemotherapy regimen and partly to disrupted sleep driven by hot flashes — a combination of natural menopause (which occurred at age 51) and the hormonal effects of treatment. She also notes occasional nausea on chemotherapy days, managed with antiemetics. Her emotional wellbeing has been supported by a breast cancer support group she joined shortly after diagnosis, which she attends biweekly and describes as invaluable.\n\n{patientName}'s lifestyle is generally healthy: she follows a Mediterranean-style diet, walks 30 minutes daily when energy permits, and has never smoked. She drinks alcohol socially, rarely more than a single glass of wine per week. She has been a patient of her primary care physician for over 15 years and maintains compliance with annual check-ups. She has a past medical history notable for Type 2 diabetes mellitus (well-controlled on metformin) and mild essential hypertension managed with lifestyle modification alone. She has no prior history of benign breast disease or prior malignancies."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
